n discourse of gender and exemplarity to epic poetry - to a Stoic framework, so as to give his reader a lucid understanding of the limits of the self and the ineluctability of natural laws.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aGrief. 4aAntike. 4aEmotionen. 4aL. Annaeus Seneca. 4aStoizismus. 4aTrostliteratur.  aL. Annaeus Seneca.  aRoman Stoicism.  aantiquity.  aconsolation literature.  aemotions.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z97831111757820 cEPUBz97831110148900 cprintz978311100742740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783111014845zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111014845zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783111014845/original  a978-3-11-117578-2 DG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA